ce:section.ce:para:
The most distinctive features of the Mg, N-CQDs different from other previously reported CQDs was their specific chromatic response to the pH values (in the range of 2.2–12.0). It was clearly found that the fluorescence color of Mg, N-CQDs changed from blue to green as the pH values of solutions altered from 12.0–5.4 (Fig. 7
                        ). Further decreasing the pH values from 5.4 to 2.2 would converse the fluorescence color of Mg, N-CQDs solution from green to yellow. A detailed investigation was further carried out on the response of fluorescence emission of Mg, N-CQDs to their pH values. As shown in Fig. S6, the fluorescence spectra of Mg, N-CQDs in buffer solutions with various pH values displayed same fluorescence spectra, confirming that pH-responsive property of Mg, N-CQDs was not resulting from interactions between Mg, N-CQDs and buffer solutions. As shown in Fig. 8
                        b, the emission peak of the Mg, N-CQDs red shifted monotonically from 495 to 535 nm as the pH values decreased from 12.0 to 5.4 (excitation at 405 nm), which was mainly caused by the deprotonation of oxygen containing functional groups, e.g., a hydroxyl and carboxyl groups (Fan et al., 2017; Miyake et al., 1989; Yuan et al., 2015). The maximum emission peak of Mg, N-CQDs was scarcely changed with further reducing the pH value of buffer solution from 5.4 to 2.2 and their fluorescence color was constant at yellow color. As shown in Fig. 8c, the maximum absorption peak of Mg, N-CQDs was shifting from 400 nm to 480 nm with decreasing the pH values from 12.0 to 2.2, evidencing that the corresponding fluorophore groups in Mg, N-CQDs were responsible for the change of fluorescence color. Meanwhile, it was clearly observed from the emission spectra of Mg, N-CQDs (Fig. 8a) that the fluorescence intensity of the Mg, N-CQDs gradually decreased with decreasing the pH values from 7.0 to 2.2. This phenomenon was might due to that the metal ligand at the edge of Mg, N-CQDs would be changed under acidic conditions as a new valence state in the metal ligand was usually formed in acidic environments (Choudhary et al., 2015; Pareek et al., 2014).
